The user is asking about "magic numbers" - what they are and why they're flagged in code reviews.

Magic numbers are hardcoded numeric literals in code that lack semantic meaning. They make code harder to read, maintain, and understand because:

1. No clear purpose - What does `if (x > 5000)` mean? 5000 what?
2. Hard to change - If the threshold needs to change, you have to find all instances
3. Context is lost - Future readers won't understand the business rule

Better practice:
```javascript
// BAD - magic number
if (timeout > 5000) { ... }

// GOOD - named constant
const MAX_TIMEOUT_MS = 5000;
if (timeout > MAX_TIMEOUT_MS) { ... }

// EVEN BETTER - configuration
const config = { timeout: 5000 };
```

